terms of this research, IARC, the International Agency of Research on

492
00:30:26.620 --> 00:30:29.300
Cancer, declared air pollution a carcinogen.

493
00:30:29.740 --> 00:30:33.580
Now, at the time, everybody was a little surprised that they went

494
00:30:33.620 --> 00:30:37.120
that far because the evidence at that point was really only

495
00:30:37.220 --> 00:30:40.880
there for lung cancer and particulate matter air pollution, specifically

496
00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:44.440
PM2.5, or the particulate matter less than 2.5 microns in

497
00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:46.196
diameter.So

498
00:30:47.156 --> 00:30:50.316
if you want to read IARC's report, which is a really beautifully written report on

499
00:30:50.356 --> 00:30:54.156
the state of the epidemiology, the toxicology, and the exposure evidence at that

500
00:30:54.216 --> 00:30:57.956
time in 2013, that's the QR code below that chunk of text.

501
00:30:58.756 --> 00:31:02.576
And what they had to work with for the epi side is somewhat

502
00:31:02.636 --> 00:31:06.416
illustrated on the graphic here. What you're seeing is that this is a

503
00:31:07.396 --> 00:31:11.156
forest plot of all of the different studies, some of which were actually available

504
00:31:11.236 --> 00:31:13.336
after IARC. You can see some of the publication dates.

505
00:31:14.216 --> 00:31:18.086
In the first column are all the studies from North America, and the studies on the

506
00:31:18.156 --> 00:31:22.136
right are from the rest of the world, and the QR code there will take you to

507
00:31:22.176 --> 00:31:24.806
that paper by Michelle Turner that has that evidence.

508
00:31:25.116 --> 00:31:28.916
This is a paper from 2021, so there's actually even

509
00:31:28.956 --> 00:31:32.186
more now. And what you'll see in this is that

510
00:31:32.616 --> 00:31:34.536
there's different... Yeah, you can actually see that.

511
00:31:34.836 --> 00:31:38.316
So the black circles are for each group of studies because people have

512
00:31:38.336 --> 00:31:41.276
reanalyzed their data multiple times as more data have come in.

513
00:31:43.116 --> 00:31:46.776
When you see down at the bottom selected studies, it's the black dots for each

514
00:31:46.816 --> 00:31:50.136
series. So a lot of these came out of the department at the Harvard School of

515
00:31:50.156 --> 00:31:51.736
Public Health, like the Harvard Six City study.

516
00:31:51.776 --> 00:31:55.596
My thesis is in there, which always makes me feel proud when I see that in the

517
00:31:55.636 --> 00:31:59.536
IARC decision. But overall, when you look at about a

518
00:31:59.576 --> 00:32:03.456
10 microgram per meter cubed increase in PM2.5,

519
00:32:03.736 --> 00:32:07.556
you see about a 13% increased risk of incidence of lung

520
00:32:07.636 --> 00:32:09.346
cancer, and that's pretty consistent around the world.

521
00:32:09.416 --> 00:32:11.976
The European studies are a little stronger than those from the US.

522
00:32:12.556 --> 00:32:16.366
But even as there's probably another 20 or so papers,

523
00:32:16.416 --> 00:32:18.416
especially the papers from Asia are really filling in.

524
00:32:18.836 --> 00:32:21.116
You see this really consistent evidence around the world.

525
00:32:21.596 --> 00:32:25.156
So again, this evidence of declaring

526
00:32:25.676 --> 00:32:29.456
air pollution a carcinogen seems to be really robust, but really, really

527
00:32:29.496 --> 00:32:32.016
was only developed on the lung cancer.

528
00:32:32.896 --> 00:32:35.976
In that report that IARC put out, they talked about, well, there's some emerging

529
00:32:36.036 --> 00:32:39.636
evidence for breast cancer, there's some emerging evidence for bladder cancer.

530
00:32:39.656 --> 00:32:42.376
But at the time, the lung cancer evidence was really the strongest.

531
00:32:43.176 --> 00:32:44.356
So that's kind of where we started.

532
00:32:45.156 --> 00:32:48.896
So in the 13 years since then, not surprisingly, there's been more research.

533
00:32:49.816 --> 00:32:53.256
And a lot of the expansion has been in different cancers.

534
00:32:53.676 --> 00:32:57.636
So again, I hinted that IARC had mentioned breast cancer as one of

535
00:32:57.696 --> 00:33:01.016
the kind of speculative research areas.

536
00:33:01.336 --> 00:33:04.196
This has really broadened out, but I think it's been an interesting story.

537
00:33:04.616 --> 00:33:07.676
So this is a recent paper. Lexy White, who's an intramural

538
00:33:08.196 --> 00:33:11.976
researcher at NIEHS, put together a consortium of

539
00:33:12.036 --> 00:33:15.516
five of the largest prospective cohorts of women in the

540
00:33:15.596 --> 00:33:19.496
US and did a large analysis of air pollution and breast cancer

541
00:33:19.576 --> 00:33:22.285
risk. So again, a lot of these studies had done their own stuff,

542
00:33:23.096 --> 00:33:26.516
slightly underpowered in a lot of cases, even for breast cancer.

543
00:33:26.536 --> 00:33:30.026
But what she saw was that when you put together all the data from all the cohorts,

544
00:33:30.436 --> 00:33:34.236
what you saw, this panel, Panel A, is the associations with

545
00:33:34.296 --> 00:33:38.176
NO2, or nitrogen dioxide, which is more of a measure of traffic.

546
00:33:38.236 --> 00:33:42.176
It comes from a lot of car exhaust. And on the right-hand side is the PM2.5

547
00:33:42.256 --> 00:33:45.516
estimates. And so what you see is that in the overall,

548
00:33:46.236 --> 00:33:50.076
when you look at all the cohorts, you do see a suggestive elevated risk of

549
00:33:50.096 --> 00:33:53.996
breast cancer, which is mostly being driven by premenopausal breast cancer

550
00:33:54.036 --> 00:33:56.966
and breast cancer among Black women and non-Hispanic White women.

551
00:33:57.656 --> 00:34:00.426
And again, confidence intervals are pretty broad on this, even putting together

552
00:34:00.436 --> 00:34:02.316
five cohorts worth of data.

553
00:34:03.156 --> 00:34:05.316
But for PM2.5, she didn't really see anything.

554
00:34:05.556 --> 00:34:09.136
So again, that PM2.5 story is really strong for lung cancer,

555
00:34:09.676 --> 00:34:12.836
but for breast cancer, not as strong. We're seeing it more with NO2.

556
00:34:12.946 --> 00:34:15.957
And this has been pretty consistent across the literature that breast cancer seems

557
00:34:15.996 --> 00:34:19.917
to be tracking more with that traffic-related air pollution than with

558
00:34:19.937 --> 00:34:21.676
PM2.5. So again,

559
00:34:22.796 --> 00:34:26.426
air pollution is a heterogeneous mixture of different things, and depending on the

560
00:34:26.496 --> 00:34:30.116
studies and the different levels of exposure that you're looking at around the

561
00:34:30.136 --> 00:34:33.536
world, we're seeing different patterns with incidence and across the different

562
00:34:33.576 --> 00:34:34.076
cancers.

563
00:34:36.216 --> 00:34:40.176
Where the research is moving, Trang kind of hinted at this in her earlier talk, is

564
00:34:40.216 --> 00:34:43.386
that newer work is really focused on those sources or

565
00:34:43.476 --> 00:34:46.616
specific sources of air pollution or specific pollutants.

566
00:34:47.276 --> 00:34:51.036
So, looking at her work, looking at wildfire

567
00:34:51.196 --> 00:34:55.156
exposure, looking at different components of PM2.5, so the

568
00:34:55.216 --> 00:34:58.106
metal levels in PM2.5, looking at things like

569
00:34:58.136 --> 00:35:00.876
dioxin or different hazardous air pollutants.

570
00:35:00.896 --> 00:35:04.276
Again, that's really where the research is going to try and give us more of a sense

571
00:35:04.796 --> 00:35:08.716
of where or which types of sources are driving different

572
00:35:08.776 --> 00:35:12.616
independent cancers. The research is also moving really quickly in survival.

573
00:35:12.696 --> 00:35:16.396
So again, all of the evidence from maybe 10 years ago was pretty much

574
00:35:16.576 --> 00:35:19.176
only on incidence, maybe some mortality studies.

575
00:35:19.596 --> 00:35:23.536
But now really focusing in on those survivor populations and trying to

576
00:35:23.596 --> 00:35:27.356
ascertain if they are more or less vulnerable to the aspects of air pollution.

577
00:35:27.956 --> 00:35:31.496
So, as Trang mentioned, she did this really elegant analysis looking at air

578
00:35:31.556 --> 00:35:34.036
pollution and wildfires using SEER Medicare data.

579
00:35:34.596 --> 00:35:38.416
So again, looking in the different SEER counties, looking at both air pollution and

580
00:35:38.456 --> 00:35:41.656
where that air pollution was coming a lot from different wildfire

581
00:35:41.676 --> 00:35:45.536
exposures. And again, showing that even for the same

582
00:35:45.596 --> 00:35:49.096
increase in air pollution exposure for PM2.5, if that

583
00:35:49.136 --> 00:35:53.006
PM2.5 was coming more from wildfires than not, you saw

584
00:35:53.136 --> 00:35:57.056
elevated risk. So again, suggesting that that wildfire PM may

585
00:35:57.176 --> 00:36:00.796
be more toxic for cancer outcomes

586
00:36:00.996 --> 00:36:04.846
than other sources of PM2.5. So again, if you're thinking with your

587
00:36:04.916 --> 00:36:08.716
regulatory hat on, then you may be wanting to go

588
00:36:08.836 --> 00:36:12.436
after wildfires more than you go after other sources of

589
00:36:12.476 --> 00:36:15.556
PM2.5, or maybe not go after anything these days.

590
00:36:17.236 --> 00:36:21.176
So trying to move-- After you study air pollution for about 10 years, you really

591
00:36:21.196 --> 00:36:23.736
just want to look at something that's good for you in the environment because air

592
00:36:23.756 --> 00:36:26.736
pollution is associated with just about everything we look at.

593
00:36:26.796 --> 00:36:30.676
So, right about 10 years ago, we as a group, and pretty much the

594
00:36:30.686 --> 00:36:34.536
literature as a whole, started really looking at nature exposure as a

595
00:36:34.556 --> 00:36:38.376
beneficial aspect of the environment that we hope to quantify the effects

596
00:36:38.456 --> 00:36:42.236
of. So greenness, as is the most common

597
00:36:42.676 --> 00:36:46.476
environmental way of looking at nature, has often been characterized

598
00:36:46.576 --> 00:36:49.836
using this measure called the Normalized Difference Vegetation Index, or

599
00:36:49.976 --> 00:36:53.672
NDVIPartially because this is available

600
00:36:53.681 --> 00:36:56.732
worldwide every 16 days at a 30-meter

601
00:36:56.772 --> 00:37:00.682
resolution since the 1980s as part of a satellite called

602
00:37:00.692 --> 00:37:04.172
Landsat. It's freely available. Used to be that it would take

603
00:37:04.212 --> 00:37:08.192
approximately six months to download a year's worth of data at 16

604
00:37:08.232 --> 00:37:09.792
days in a 30-meter scale.

605
00:37:10.652 --> 00:37:13.332
Now, thanks to Google Earth Engine, it takes about a day and a half.

606
00:37:13.752 --> 00:37:17.462
So my trainees are much happier to spend time doing their analyses than downloading

607
00:37:17.532 --> 00:37:20.932
data for months and months. So this map just gives you a sense of what greenness

608
00:37:20.952 --> 00:37:23.042
looks like. This is July of 2000.

609
00:37:24.052 --> 00:37:24.752
The Northeast

610
00:37:25.932 --> 00:37:29.632
and the eastern half of the United States has more of this than the

611
00:37:29.672 --> 00:37:33.592
western half, but again, 30-meter resolution, you can get down to a pretty small

612
00:37:33.632 --> 00:37:33.912
scale.

613
00:37:34.852 --> 00:37:38.472
So how is NDVI calculated? It's clearly an index, so there's going to be a

614
00:37:38.532 --> 00:37:42.492
ratio involved. And so what it is, is we're using satellite data

615
00:37:42.572 --> 00:37:45.132
using two different wavelengths.

616
00:37:45.592 --> 00:37:49.522
And what this gives you a measure of is actually the photosynthetic activity in

617
00:37:49.572 --> 00:37:53.492
that 30-meter pixel. So if you look at this graphic from NASA,

618
00:37:53.612 --> 00:37:57.292
you have two trees, and you're looking at the ratio of the near-infrared

619
00:37:57.372 --> 00:38:01.322
band and the visible band, and what you can see is that the

620
00:38:01.412 --> 00:38:05.222
tree on the left is healthier than the tree on the right, and so it has a higher

621
00:38:05.432 --> 00:38:09.362
NDVI for that specific tree. On the right is a graphic actually from

622
00:38:09.452 --> 00:38:12.212
a company that will offer to fly over your crops.

623
00:38:12.652 --> 00:38:16.272
So this measure was actually originally developed by USDA as a measure of crop

624
00:38:16.312 --> 00:38:16.572
health.

625
00:38:17.412 --> 00:38:20.072
And what they'll do is they'll fly over your crops, and so they're giving you an

626
00:38:20.132 --> 00:38:23.652
estimate of what this looks like. So if you have zero for your

627
00:38:23.732 --> 00:38:27.152
NDVI, it's either bare ground or dead plants.

628
00:38:27.532 --> 00:38:30.892
So no photosynthetic activity. So it could be just the winter.

629
00:38:31.352 --> 00:38:35.272
If you have a measure of one, it means in that pixel that you're measuring, it is

630
00:38:35.312 --> 00:38:38.192
fully covered in highly photosynthetically active material.

631
00:38:38.612 --> 00:38:41.752
Now, again, this doesn't tell you anything about the aesthetics of that.

632
00:38:41.792 --> 00:38:45.752
It could be a weedy, overgrown lot that just has a lot of green grass or a

633
00:38:45.772 --> 00:38:49.591
beautifully landscaped, manicured garden or something.

634
00:38:49.632 --> 00:38:52.842
So again, this is really just pure photosynthetic activity is what we're

635
00:38:52.892 --> 00:38:56.882
measuring. So there was a recent article, actually now

636
00:38:57.012 --> 00:39:00.932
2023, that came out trying to look at what was the

637
00:39:01.032 --> 00:39:04.892
state of the literature on NDVI and cancer

638
00:39:04.972 --> 00:39:08.772
incidence specifically. So you can see here grouped by the different cancer

639
00:39:08.812 --> 00:39:12.092
types, what the state of the literature was three years ago.

640
00:39:12.782 --> 00:39:16.252
And it's heterogeneous. So what you can see is for things like prostate

641
00:39:16.332 --> 00:39:20.252
cancer, lung cancer, you see that there

642
00:39:20.312 --> 00:39:24.012
do appear to be beneficial effects of greenness on cancer

643
00:39:24.072 --> 00:39:27.771
incidence, but that there's a lot of heterogeneity both across

644
00:39:27.812 --> 00:39:29.432
cancer site and within cancer site.

645
00:39:29.472 --> 00:39:32.912
And you can see that there's research here from

646
00:39:33.102 --> 00:39:35.112
mainly France, Israel, China, and the US,

647
00:39:36.092 --> 00:39:39.072
and that actually the whole bottom section of this graph is coming from a single

648
00:39:39.132 --> 00:39:42.592
study in China. So again, we're not seeing consistent

649
00:39:42.652 --> 00:39:46.572
results here for any given cancer or any given place in the

650
00:39:46.592 --> 00:39:48.422
world. Now, I'll say in the last three years,

651
00:39:49.852 --> 00:39:52.752
most of the papers that have been published have been showing beneficial effects.

652
00:39:53.232 --> 00:39:56.892
But again, there's a lot of heterogeneity, partially because NDVI just

653
00:39:56.952 --> 00:39:59.352
means photosynthetic activity, right?

654
00:39:59.452 --> 00:40:00.422
It may not mean that it's--

655
00:40:01.572 --> 00:40:05.442
A lot of the hypothesized mechanisms are that it increases physical activity,

656
00:40:06.012 --> 00:40:07.672
it reduces overall stress levels.

657
00:40:07.812 --> 00:40:10.732
Again, those have different associations with different cancer sites.

658
00:40:12.872 --> 00:40:16.752
But again, like everything else, these measures of how we think about the

659
00:40:16.772 --> 00:40:18.392
built environment are evolving rapidly.

660
00:40:19.072 --> 00:40:23.052
So emerging research that has come out in probably the last maybe three to five

661
00:40:23.132 --> 00:40:27.112
years, maybe one to five, is using images of locations.

662
00:40:27.192 --> 00:40:30.772
So instead of using satellite data coming down from thousands of feet

663
00:40:30.872 --> 00:40:34.632
above your house, we can use things like Google Street View or

664
00:40:34.712 --> 00:40:38.292
other street-level imagery to be able to quantify measures of the built

665
00:40:38.332 --> 00:40:41.262
environment. So for example, this is the Google Street View image outside of the

666
00:40:41.272 --> 00:40:44.972
convention center. You can see a lot of hardscape, some plants,

667
00:40:45.152 --> 00:40:48.472
some trees, but in general, not a lot of green space, not a lot of

668
00:40:48.532 --> 00:40:50.912
photosynthetic activity going on right outside the building.

669
00:40:52.272 --> 00:40:56.072
Now, what you can do with this is you can couple these images with machine

670
00:40:56.112 --> 00:40:59.442
learning algorithms that have been developed for lots of different purposes, and

671
00:40:59.452 --> 00:41:03.292
you can actually quantify the amount of different classes

672
00:41:03.352 --> 00:41:06.832
of information. So for example, what you're seeing in this image as

673
00:41:06.872 --> 00:41:10.802
it's going through London is you can see that you can quantify pixels as

674
00:41:10.872 --> 00:41:14.612
if, are they road? Are they humans? Are they cars? Are they trees?

675
00:41:15.872 --> 00:41:19.192
And so again, instead of just being able to say, "Here's the amount of

676
00:41:19.212 --> 00:41:23.092
photosynthetic activity in a 30-meter pixel," we can actually quantify,

677
00:41:23.492 --> 00:41:26.032
are there trees? Are there grasses? Are there plants?

678
00:41:26.112 --> 00:41:29.512
Are there agricultural lands that may be having pesticides applied to them?

679
00:41:30.092 --> 00:41:33.782
We can identify street features like bike lanes or sidewalks that may

680
00:41:33.832 --> 00:41:37.312
help with increasing physical activity in different areas.

681
00:41:37.672 --> 00:41:41.242
If we're interested in exposures among older individuals, we can look for things

682
00:41:41.272 --> 00:41:44.432
like street furniture that may encourage them to go outside and interact with their

683
00:41:44.472 --> 00:41:46.332
neighborhoods and their neighbors.

684
00:41:46.852 --> 00:41:50.732
We can identify things like infrastructure, so things like bus shelters, all

685
00:41:50.792 --> 00:41:54.192
kinds of different things that maybe tell us about different environmental factors

686
00:41:54.232 --> 00:41:54.972
in the environment.

687
00:41:55.952 --> 00:41:58.922
Also, it just looks really cool to be able to show this graphic where it's in

688
00:41:58.932 --> 00:42:00.452
real-time making all the pixels colored.

689
00:42:01.362 --> 00:42:04.432
So what does this look like if you're doing this for-- We're doing it for--

690
00:42:04.512 --> 00:42:07.692
Apparently, my colleague Peter James just finished a project where he

691
00:42:07.732 --> 00:42:08.632
classified

692
00:42:09.692 --> 00:42:12.912
about 350 million images for the entire US

693
00:42:13.452 --> 00:42:16.632
across a 20-year spatial scale. So you have

694
00:42:16.852 --> 00:42:18.952
multiple images across time.

695
00:42:19.772 --> 00:42:23.132
And what you can do, again, is you run one of these AI machine learning

696
00:42:23.692 --> 00:42:26.852
algorithms on this, and you can classify all the pixels.

697
00:42:27.152 --> 00:42:30.072
So Google Street View takes four images off the top of the camera,

698
00:42:31.432 --> 00:42:34.172
so you get the whole 360-degree rotation.

699
00:42:34.752 --> 00:42:37.072
And what you can do is you can quantify the images.

700
00:42:37.152 --> 00:42:38.152
So these images here

701
00:42:39.012 --> 00:42:41.612
have approximately 23% trees

702
00:42:42.132 --> 00:42:45.925
andDown, shift it down a little bit, and 22% road,

703
00:42:46.296 --> 00:42:50.216
and 13% grass. So again, you can take this and you can assign, if somebody

704
00:42:50.256 --> 00:42:54.096
was living right next to this image, you can assign them that

705
00:42:54.136 --> 00:42:57.896
information instead of just saying they have an NDVI of 6.6, right?

706
00:42:57.956 --> 00:43:01.656
So now we're able to distinguish the beneficial effects of trees versus plants

707
00:43:01.716 --> 00:43:05.486
versus greenness. And in a lot of our initial work, we're actually seeing that

708
00:43:05.516 --> 00:43:08.956
contrary to the NDVI, we only see benefits from trees.

709
00:43:09.116 --> 00:43:12.436
We're not really seeing benefits from other plants or grasses, and in some cases,

710
00:43:12.456 --> 00:43:15.756
grasses are harmful. So we're trying to figure out if that's because grasses are an

711
00:43:15.796 --> 00:43:16.856
indication of sprawl,

712
00:43:17.676 --> 00:43:21.116
if they're an indication of the lawn chemicals that we like to put on our lawns.

713
00:43:21.856 --> 00:43:24.476
But we're still trying to figure out what's wrong with the grass.

714
00:43:25.136 --> 00:43:29.096
Which is interesting because city planners, when they heard increased NDVI,

715
00:43:29.636 --> 00:43:33.296
heard increased grass, because it's the cheapest way to get a lot of photosynthetic

716
00:43:33.336 --> 00:43:33.686
activity.

717
00:43:35.076 --> 00:43:36.966
So what are the mechanisms that underlie this?

718
00:43:36.996 --> 00:43:40.696
So again, that paper by Michelle Turner and colleagues had a really brilliant

719
00:43:40.736 --> 00:43:43.196
summary of the mechanistic data for air pollution.

720
00:43:44.616 --> 00:43:48.456
And again, it's broad. So air pollution particles can actually

721
00:43:48.495 --> 00:43:52.336
translocate across your lungs, get into your circulation, and deposit in

722
00:43:52.396 --> 00:43:55.656
every tissue in your body. They actually can go up your

723
00:43:56.616 --> 00:44:00.316
nasal pathway and reach your brain directly, so they can cross the blood-brain

